- write pure and functional code which aims to be deterministic
- don't add mindless commentary, comment when you've done something complicated. good code should be readable itself.
- no need to run tests after every change, unless you have good reason to
- less code is always better. aim to write as concise readable code as possible. do not repeat yourself, avoid bloat. your overarching goal is to produce as small a diff as possible while completing any task
- don't delete things for no reason, if not asked to. especially not commented out code or 'unused' functions. you can suggest deletions, but do not do it yourself unprompted.
- do not add emojis to comments or debug logs
- favor switch statements over if else if else if etc, when there are many options.
- Assert assumptions - ie I'd rather fail fast and throw an error which I can learn from and improve the project with
- when debugging, prepend related logs with specific strings, so that we can filter for them in the browser easily.
- don't try to rebuild the project after every change. that's pointless. unless theres an error which makes this seem necessary.
